figgy.title: "Attach an existing resource by ID" on record page does not remove the attached resource from its previous parent.

comments.body:
There is probably bad data in figgy -- resources with multiple parents. What is the scale? Can we do a clean up? How would we know which is the correct parent?

If you come across this scenario, the way to clean it up is along the lines of:

```ruby
> host = query_service.find_by(id: <host_id>)

> children = Wayfinder.for(host).members

> all_parents = children.flat_map{ |child| Wayfinder.for(child).parents }.uniq

> all_parents = all_parents - [host]

> all_parents.each do |p|
>   p.member_ids = []
>   persister.save(resource: p)
> end

> all_parents.each do |p|
>   change_set = ChangeSet.for(p)
>   ChangeSetPersister.default.delete(change_set: change_set)
> end
```
Resources should be removed from the previous parent.

oawaiver.title: Implementing support for Account authorization for accessing WaiverInfo
Ensure that user accounts with admin. privileges can access all WaiverInfo records

comments.body:
I am sorry, I am afraid there seems to be some difficulty in identifying why this is problematic. Investigating the legacy database, I observe that there are only two records created by the reporting user:

```
MariaDB [oawaiver_legacy]> select id,requester,requester_email,created_at from waiver_infos where requester like 'yl7';
+------+-----------+-------------------+---------------------+
| id   | requester | requester_email   | created_at          |
+------+-----------+-------------------+---------------------+
| 1099 | yl7       | yl7@~ | 2020-04-28 13:53:36 |
| 1109 | yl7       | yl7@~ | 2020-05-14 21:14:16 |
+------+-----------+-------------------+---------------------+
2 rows in set (0.002 sec)
```

This corresponds with the records stored within the current production database:

```
oawaiver_prod=# select id,requester,requester_email from waiver_infos where requester_email like '%yl7%' or author_email like '%yl7%';
  id  | requester |  requester_email
------+-----------+-------------------
 1099 | yl7       | yl7@~
 1109 | yl7       | yl7@~
 1222 | yl7       | yl7@~
```

Reviewing the error reported by the end-user, it is my impression that they were expecting more records:

```
Have we finished the data migration yet? I found that we lost all the prior waiver data in the current Waiver DB. When I reivew prior waiver requests, I can only see three records, two were requested recently and one was the test by me.
```

The user *should* only be seeing prior waiver requests, as these were the only records stored within the legacy database. Further, the query constructed for the legacy database can be found at the following:

```ruby
def index_mine
    do_index({'Requester or Author' => @user_email},
             WaiverInfo.find_by_email(@user_email));
  end
```
https://github.com/PrincetonUniversityLibrary/oa-waiverdatabase/blob/master/app/controllers/waiver_infos_controller.rb#L74

Just to confirm that all records have been successfully migrated, please see the following:

```bash
MariaDB [oawaiver_legacy]> select count(id) from waiver_infos;
+-----------+
| count(id) |
+-----------+
|      1212 |
+-----------+
```

```bash
oawaiver_prod=# select count(id) from waiver_infos;
 count
-------
  1217
(1 row)
```

After enquiring further with the reporting user, the following was determined to be the case:

```
I was not looking for the records requested by me. I meant all records. Maybe my account privilege has been changed in the new DB. I was an admin of waiver DB. So were the staff and students. When login, we were able to view and search through all records. With the new DB, I only can see 3 records.
```
